"1535–1617":"1535–1617","1540–Female":"1540–Overleden","1542–Male":"1542–Overleden","1510–1557":"1510–1557","1 February 1557":"1 februari 1557","1560":"1560","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","1557":"1557","1534":"1534","1532":"1532","1510":"1510","15 September 1540":"15 september 1540","19 February 1542":"19 februari 1542","1542":"1542","1541":"1541","1540":"1540","1562":"1562","about 1510":"circa 1510","about 1531":"circa 1531","1617":"1617","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","Walsham le Willows, Suffolk, England":"Walsham le Willows, Suffolk, England","Walsham Le Willows, Suffolk, England":"Walsham le Willows, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"en":{"about 1510–1557":"about 1510–1557","1515–1558":"1515–1558","1541–1560":"1541–1560","1532–1562":"1532–1562","1534–Female":"1534–Deceased","1535–1617":"1535–1617","1540–Female":"1540–Deceased","1542–Male":"1542–Deceased","1510–1557":"1510–1557","1 February 1557":"1 February 1557","1560":"1560","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","1557":"1557","1534":"1534","1532":"1532","1510":"1510","15 September 1540":"15 September 1540","19 February 1542":"19 February 1542","1542":"1542","1541":"1541","1540":"1540","1562":"1562","about 1510":"about 1510","about 1531":"about 1531","1617":"1617","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","Walsham le Willows, Suffolk, England":"Walsham le Willows, Suffolk, England","Walsham Le Willows, Suffolk, England":"Walsham le Willows, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Waller","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>waler</i>, <i>waliere</i>, <i>walour</i>, <i>waller</i> ‘builder of walls, mason’.","English: in Sussex, perhaps a topographic name for someone who lived by a prominent wall.","English: topographic name for someone who lived by a spring, stream, or man-made well, from Middle English <i>waller</i>, a derivative of Middle English <i>walle</i>, Old English <i>wælle</i>, <i>wælle</i>. It is a West Midlands dialect form of   Weller  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wallar","meanings":["English: variant of   Waller  ."]},{"name":"Weller","meanings":["English (Surrey, Sussex, and Kent): topographic name for someone who lived by a spring, stream, or man-made well, from Middle English <i>weller</i>, <i>willer</i>, an agent derivative of Middle English <i>welle</i> (in southern England) and <i>wille</i> (in south western England), from Old English <i>wella</i>, <i>well(e)</i>, <i>wiella</i>, <i>wielle</i>, <i>willa</i>, <i>wyll(a)</i>, <i>wylle</i>. This type of name, a topographic term + <i>-er</i>, is particularly typical of Sussex and its neigbouring counties.","English: occupational name for someone who casts metal or who boils salt, from Middle English <i>weller</i>, <i>willer</i>, a derivative with <i>-er</i> of Old English <i>wellan</i>, <i>wiellan</i> ‘to boil’. Compare 5 below.","North German: variant of   Welle  , cognate with 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":39,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Nicholas Waller was born about 1510, in Walsham le Willows, Suffolk, England. He married Susan Chapman about 1531, in Walsham le Willows, Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 3 daughters. He died in 1557, at the age of 48, and was buried in Walsham le Willows, Suffolk, England."},"et":{"about 1510–1557":"umbes 1510–1557","1515–1558":"1515–1558","1541–1560":"1541–1560","1532–1562":"1532–1562","1534–Female":"1534–Surnud","1535–1617":"1535–1617","1540–Female":"1540–Surnud","1542–Male":"1542–Surnud","1510–1557":"1510–1557","1 February 1557":"1. veebruar 1557","1560":"1560","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","1557":"1557","1534":"1534","1532":"1532","1510":"1510","15 September 1540":"15. september 1540","19 February 1542":"19. veebruar 1542","1542":"1542","1541":"1541","1540":"1540","1562":"1562","about 1510":"umbes 1510","about 1531":"umbes 1531","1617":"1617","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","Walsham le Willows, Suffolk, England":"Walsham le Willows, Suffolk, England","Walsham Le Willows, Suffolk, England":"Walsham le Willows, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"about 1510–1557":"noin 1510–1557","1515–1558":"1515–1558",